nting in Michigan's Thumb — Guided Hunts with Hotshot Outfitters\\u003c/h1\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eCrow hunting is the best wingshooting you're not doing. That's not an exaggeration. When crows work a decoy spread and you're calling them into close range, the shooting action can rival any upland species you'll hunt in Michigan. Crows are legal game birds in Michigan, they're abundant across Huron County's agricultural landscape, and hunting them does genuine good for the farmers whose fields we operate on. Hotshot Outfitters offers guided crow hunts in Michigan's Thumb, and if you've never hunted crows, or if you're a seasoned crow hunter looking for new ground, this is worth a close read.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003chr\\u003e\\n\\u003ch2\\u003eThe Case for Crow Hunting in Michigan\\u003c/h2\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eCrows are, in a word, smart. They are widely regarded as among the most intelligent birds in North America, and hunting them demands a different set of skills than most wingshooting pursuits. You have to call convincingly, set realistic decoy spreads, stay concealed, and read crow behavior in real time to keep birds committed. When it comes together, a crow hunt can produce dozens of shooting opportunities in a single morning.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eBeyond the pure sport of it, crows are a legitimate nuisance in agricultural areas. They raid corn plantings, hit grain fields, mob the nests of other game birds, and damage crops in ways that put them squarely in conflict with the farmers who allow us to hunt their land. Crow hunting in Michigan is farmer-friendly, and that matters to us. When we manage crow populations on the properties we operate, we maintain the landowner relationships that make all of our guided hunts possible.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eHuron County's combination of crop agriculture, woodlots, and proximity to Lake Huron makes it exceptional crow country. Crows roost communally and travel predictable corridors between roost sites and feeding areas. Our guides know those corridors.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003chr\\u003e\\n\\u003ch2\\u003eMichigan Crow Season — Dates and Legal Framework\\u003c/h2\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eCrows are classified as migratory game birds under the Federal Migratory Bird Treaty Act, which means their seasons are set cooperatively between the U.S. Fish \\u0026#x26; Wildlife Service and individual states. Michigan has established crow hunting seasons that provide generous windows for hunting while protecting nesting periods.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eMichigan's current crow hunting framework includes open seasons generally in two windows:\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cul\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eAugust 1 through September 30\\u003c/strong\\u003e\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eFebruary 1 through March 31\\u003c/strong\\u003e\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003c/ul\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eOutside of those formal season windows, crows may not be taken under hunting regulations. However, during those open periods, there are no bag limits on crows in Michigan — hunting is seven days a week during open season.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eIt's also worth noting that Michigan law allows for the taking of crows under depredation provisions when they are actively destroying crops or threatening agricultural operations, outside of hunting season — but this is a separate legal framework from sport hunting and requires specific conditions to be met. For our guided hunts, we operate within the established Michigan open crow hunting seasons.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eAlways verify current season dates and regulations at the \\u003ca href=\\\"https://www.michigan.gov/dnr\\\"\\u003eMI DNR website\\u003c/a\\u003e before your hunt.\\u003c/strong\\u003e Federal and state crow regulations can change, and it's the hunter's responsibility to know current rules.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003chr\\u003e\\n\\u003ch2\\u003eWhat to Expect on a Guided Crow Hunt\\u003c/h2\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eCrow hunting is a team sport. It works best with multiple shooters positioned in tight concealment, calling together or in sequence, and shooting quickly when crows commit to the spread. Here's how Hotshot Outfitters runs a crow hunt:\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eSetup\\u003c/strong\\u003e: Your guide will scout the area prior to your hunt, locating active crow travel routes and feeding areas. We'll establish a hide — typically natural vegetation, brush, or pop-up blinds — near the decoy spread with clear shooting lanes in multiple directions.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eCalling\\u003c/strong\\u003e: Crow calling is an art. Electronic callers are legal in Michigan for crow hunting and are effective for producing the distress, assembly, and owl-alarm calls that pull crows from a distance. Mouth calls add realism in close. Your guide will manage the calling sequence to keep birds committed.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eDecoys\\u003c/strong\\u003e: A combination of full-body crow decoys and an owl decoy (crows harass owls instinctively — it's one of the most reliable calls you can run) set up on fence posts, brush piles, and the ground produces realistic presentations. We'll set the spread for the wind conditions and approach angles on your hunt day.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eThe Shooting\\u003c/strong\\u003e: When it works, crows will come in fast and in numbers. You must stay concealed until the guide calls the shot, then shoot quickly and decisively. Crows that flare and survive will not come back. Coordination among hunters matters — set expectations before the birds arrive.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003chr\\u003e\\n\\u003ch2\\u003eTerrain and Property\\u003c/h2\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eHuron County is prime crow hunting territory. The agricultural landscape — corn, soybeans, sugar beets — provides consistent food sources that concentrate crows in predictable areas throughout the season. Woodlot edges and isolated timber stands serve as roost sites. The corridors between roosts and feed fields are where we position our setups.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eOur guides have 20+ years of experience working this specific landscape, and that translates directly into better crow hunting. Finding where crows want to be on a given morning is half the battle. We've already done that work on the properties we access.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003chr\\u003e\\n\\u003ch2\\u003eWing-Shooting Practice: An Honest Recommendation\\u003c/h2\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eIf you're preparing for duck, goose, pheasant, or any other wingshooting season, a crow hunt is the best practice available. The shooting is fast, angles are unpredictable, and crows are not easy targets. A morning of crow hunting will tune your swing and improve your lead-reading faster than a round of clay targets.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eSerious waterfowl hunters who want to dial in their shooting before duck and goose season opens — which typically runs into fall — will find that August crow season lines up perfectly as pre-season prep. You're shooting the same choke tubes and loads you'll use on ducks, in field conditions, at moving targets that don't follow a clay pigeon's arc.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003chr\\u003e\\n\\u003ch2\\u003eLicensing and What You Need\\u003c/h2\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eCrow hunting in Michigan requires:\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cul\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eValid Michigan Hunting License\\u003c/strong\\u003e (base small game license covers migratory birds in Michigan's licensing framework, but confirm current requirements with MI DNR)\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eCompliance with Federal Migratory Bird Treaty Act regulations regarding species-specific rules\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003c/ul\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eBecause crows are federally classified as migratory birds, verify the current federal and state framework at the time of your hunt. Requirements can include compliance with federal non-toxic shot regulations in certain situations — your guide will advise on applicable rules for the properties we hunt.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003chr\\u003e\\n\\u003ch2\\u003eWhat We Supply vs. What You Bring\\u003c/h2\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eHotshot Outfitters provides:\\u003c/strong\\u003e\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cul\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eGuide with 20+ years of local crow hunting experience\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eDecoy spread setup and breakdown\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eElectronic caller and calling strategy management\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eScouted locations on private agricultural ground\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eConcealment setup and hide construction\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003c/ul\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eYou bring:\\u003c/strong\\u003e\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cul\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eValid Michigan hunting license\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eShotgun — 12-gauge preferred; 20-gauge works fine\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eAmmunition: #7.5, #8, or #6 shot; high-velocity target loads work well for crow\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eClothing in muted earth tones or camouflage (crows will bust a brown shirt at 200 yards — concealment is not optional)\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eFace mask or face paint — crows key on the human face\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eGloves — hands are the second thing crows see\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eEar protection\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003c/ul\\u003e\\n\\u003chr\\u003e\\n\\u003ch2\\u003eGear Notes for Crow Hunting\\u003c/h2\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eConcealment is the single most important gear consideration for crow hunting. These birds will identify and flare from a hunter at distances that would make most hunters skeptical. Full camouflage — face, hands, and all exposed skin — is baseline. Pop-up blinds are effective when natural vegetation is insufficient. Your gun barrel should be covered or have a matte finish. Glare from a blued barrel or scope has killed more crow setups than bad calling.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eFor shotguns, an open choke gives you better patterns at the typical 15–35 yard range where crows commit. Improved cylinder or modified is the call. If you're shooting birds at longer range during early passes, tighten up — but most killing shots happen inside 40 yards when birds are called properly.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eEar protection is worth mentioning because the shooting volume in a good crow hunt can be high. Bring electronic ear protection that lets you hear calling and guide communication while protecting your hearing.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003chr\\u003e\\n\\u003ch2\\u003eFrequently Asked Questions\\u003c/h2\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eQ: When is the best time to go crow hunting in Michigan?\\u003c/strong\\u003e\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eAugust and early September, when crops are in the fields and crow populations are at summer highs, can produce huge numbers of birds. The February–March window is also productive, particularly after winter has pushed crows into tight feeding patterns. Both seasons have their character. August is warmer and birds are abundant; February is cold but crow behavior becomes predictable around food sources.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eQ: Are there bag limits on crows in Michigan?\\u003c/strong\\u003e\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eCurrently, there are no bag limits on crows during the established open Michigan crow hunting seasons. However, regulations can change — always verify with the MI DNR before your hunt. Bag limits can be amended seasonally.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eQ: Can I use my regular hunting license for crow hunting?\\u003c/strong\\u003e\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eMichigan hunting license requirements for migratory birds can involve federal stamps and state licenses depending on the season and species. Verify the current licensing requirements with the MI DNR. Your guide will brief you on what's required for your specific hunt.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eQ: What's the best calling strategy for Michigan crows?\\u003c/strong\\u003e\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eA combination of assembly calls, distress calls, and owl alarm calls tends to produce the most consistent results. Electronic callers allow you to run multiple calls in sequence, which is more realistic than a single call repeated. Your guide will manage the calling — your job is to stay concealed and be ready to shoot.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eQ: Is crow hunting legal year-round in Michigan?\\u003c/strong\\u003e\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eNo. Michigan's crow hunting season is limited to two windows: August 1–September 30 and February 1–March 31. Outside those seasons, sport hunting for crows is prohibited under the Migratory Bird Treaty Act framework. Verify current season dates with the MI DNR each year.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eQ: How many shooters work best for a crow hunt?\\u003c/strong\\u003e\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eTwo to four shooters is typically the sweet spot. With more than four hunters, concealment becomes harder and coordination breaks down. Two hunters working as a team, with one focused on left-to-right crossing shots and one on the approach angle, can be devastatingly efficient.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003chr\\u003e\\n\\u003ch2\\u003eBook Your Michigan Crow Hunt\\u003c/h2\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eCrow hunting in Michigan's Thumb is fast, challenging, and criminally underrated. Hotshot Outfitters puts you on the right ground with the right setup to make it happen. Whether you're sharpening your wingshooting before duck season or you've been chasing crows your whole hunting life, we'll put you in position to have a morning worth talking about.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eContact us for current season availability and to get on the schedule.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003ePhone:\\u003c/strong\\u003e (989) 551-4551 or (989) 670-4336\\n\\u003cstrong\\u003eAddress:\\u003c/strong\\u003e 6900 Huron City Road, Port Hope, MI 48468\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eTwo seasons a year. Don't let them pass without making a call.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,\"12:[[\\\"$\\\",\\\"script\\\",null,{\\\"type\\\":\\\"application/ld+json\\\",\\\"dangerouslySetInnerHTML\\\":{\\\"__html\\\":\\\"{\\\\\\\"@context\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"https://schema.org\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"@type\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"Article\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"headline\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"Crow Hunting in Michigan | Guided Hunts with Hotshot Outfitters\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"description\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"Guided crow hunting in Michigan's Thumb with Hotshot Outfitters. Year-round wingshooting, fast action, farmer-friendly nuisance control. Port Hope, MI.\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"image\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"https://hotshotoutfitters.com/images/michigan-hunting-crow-michigan-01.webp\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"author\\\\\\\":{\\\\\\\"@type\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"Organization\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"name\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"Hotshot Outfitters\\\\\\\"},\\\\\\\"publisher\\\\\\\":{\\\\\\\"@type\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"Organization\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"name\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"Hotshot Outfitters\\\\\\\"},\\\\\\\"mainEntityOfPage\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"https://hotshotoutfitters.com/hunts/crow\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"about\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"Crow hunting in Michigan\\\\\\\"}\\\"}}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"section\\\",null,{\\\"className\\\":\\\"relative pt-32 pb-16 lg:pt-40 lg:pb-24 overflow-hidden\\\",\\\"children\\\":[[\\\"$\\\",\\\"$L1b\\\",null,{\\\"src\\\":\\\"/images/michigan-hunting-crow-michigan-01.webp\\\",\\\"alt\\\":\\\"Michigan crow hunting wing-shooting on a guided hunt in Huron County with Hotshot Outfitters\\\",\\\"fill\\\":true,\\\"priority\\\":true,\\\"sizes\\\"